<subSubSection pageId="653" pageNumber="654" type="nomenclature">
<paragraph pageId="653" pageNumber="654">
Genus 
<taxonomicName LSID="D25EF3F4-9A6F-786E-C0AC-B22C400562E8" authority="Newman, 1838" authorityName="Newman" authorityYear="1838" class="Insecta" family="Carabidae" genus="Amphasia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Amphasia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="653" pageNumber="654" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Amphasia Newman, 1838</taxonomicName>
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection lastPageId="654" lastPageNumber="655" pageId="653" pageNumber="654" type="reference_group">
<paragraph lastPageId="654" lastPageNumber="655" pageId="653" pageNumber="654">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Newman" authorityYear="1838" class="Insecta" family="Carabidae" genus="Amphasia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Coleoptera" pageId="653" pageNumber="654" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Amphasia</taxonomicName>
Newman, 1838a: 388. Type species: 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Newman" authorityYear="1838" class="Insecta" family="Carabidae" genus="Amphasia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Coleoptera" pageId="653" pageNumber="654" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="fulvicollis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="653" pageNumber="654">Amphasia fulvicollis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Newman, 1838 (= 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Say" authorityYear="1823" class="Insecta" family="Carabidae" genus="Feronia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Coleoptera" pageId="653" pageNumber="654" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="interstitialis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="653" pageNumber="654">Feronia interstitialis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Say, 1823) by monotypy. Etymology. From the Greek 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="653" pageNumber="654">amphi</emphasis>
<pageBreakToken pageId="654" pageNumber="655" start="start">(</pageBreakToken>
double) and 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="654" pageNumber="655">phasis</emphasis>
(appearance), probably alluding to the presence in the adults of character states found in two related genera (&quot;apparently partaking of the characters of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Latreille" authorityYear="1802" class="Hexapoda" family="Carabidae" genus="Harpalus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Coleoptera" pageId="654" pageNumber="655" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="654" pageNumber="655">Harpalus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Chaudoir" authorityYear="1843" genus="Mazoreus" lsidName="" pageId="654" pageNumber="655" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="654" pageNumber="655">Mazoreus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
&quot;) [feminine]. According to Duponchel (1840b: 374), the name 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Newman" authorityYear="1838" class="Insecta" family="Carabidae" genus="Amphasia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Coleoptera" pageId="654" pageNumber="655" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="654" pageNumber="655">Amphasia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
derives from the Greek 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="654" pageNumber="655">amphi</emphasis>
(around, on both sides) and 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="654" pageNumber="655">asis</emphasis>
(slime, mud, by extension marsh); there is no evidence in Newman (1838) pointing to that interpretation.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="654" pageNumber="655" type="diversity">
<paragraph pageId="654" pageNumber="655">Diversity.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="654" pageNumber="655">Two North American species arrayed in two subgenera.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="654" pageNumber="655" type="identification">
<paragraph pageId="654" pageNumber="655">Identification.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="654" pageNumber="655">
Lindroth (1968: 860-861) covered both species in his treatment of the genus 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Dejean" authorityYear="1829" class="Hexapoda" family="Carabidae" genus="Anisodactylus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Coleoptera" pageId="654" pageNumber="655" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="654" pageNumber="655">Anisodactylus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="654" pageNumber="655" type="taxonomic note">
<paragraph pageId="654" pageNumber="655">Taxonomic Note.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="654" pageNumber="655">
Lindroth (1968: 860) regarded this taxon as a subgenus of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Dejean" authorityYear="1829" class="Hexapoda" family="Carabidae" genus="Anisodactylus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Coleoptera" pageId="654" pageNumber="655" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="654" pageNumber="655">Anisodactylus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
while Noonan (1973: 347) treated it as a valid genus. Larval characters support 
<normalizedToken originalValue="Noonanâ€™s">Noonan's</normalizedToken>
view (Bousquet and Tchang 1992: Fig. 42).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
